Merge Two Sorted Patient Queues

In a hospital management system in Madurai, two departments maintain separate patient token lists, each already sorted in non-decreasing order of priority number. At the central desk, both queues must be merged into a single sorted queue so that service order remains correct.

Given two sorted lists, merge them into one sorted list.

To make the result more informative for evaluation, print:

the merged sorted list
the total number of elements in the merged list

Input format :
The first line contains an integer n — the number of elements in the first sorted list
The second line contains n space-separated integers
The third line contains an integer m — the number of elements in the second sorted list
The fourth line contains m space-separated integers
When n = 0 or m = 0, the corresponding line may be left empty.
Output format :
First line: print the merged sorted list as space-separated integers
Second line: print Count: x, where x is the total number of elements in the merged list

Code constraints :
0 <= n, m <= 50
1 <= n + m <= 50
-100 <= element <= 100
Both input lists are already sorted in non-decreasing order.

Sample test cases :
Input 1 :
3
1 2 4
3
1 3 4
Output 1 :
1 1 2 3 4 4


Input 2 :
0
1
10
Output 2 :
10


Solution:

// You are using GCC
#include<bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main(){
    
    int n;
    cin >> n;
    
    vector<int> arr(n);
    
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){
        cin >> arr[i];
    }
    
    int m;
    cin >> m;
    
    vector<int> arr1(m);
    
    for(int i = 0; i < m; i++){
        cin >> arr1[i];
    }
    
    vector<int> res;
    
    int i = 0;
    int j = 0;
    
    while(i < n && j < m){
        
        if(arr[i] <= arr1[j]){
            res.push_back(arr[i]);
            i++;
        }
        else{
            res.push_back(arr1[j]);
            j++;
        }
    }
    
    while(i < n){
        res.push_back(arr[i]);
        i++;
    }
    
    while(j < m){
        res.push_back(arr1[j]);
        j++;
    }
    
    for(int x : res){
        cout << x << " ";
    }
    
    return 0;
}
